HOW TO PRINT "Hello world":
// hello_world.c: (file name)
#include <stdio.h>

// Print "Hello, world!" followed by newline and exit
int main(void) {
  printf("Hello, world!\n");
  return 0;
}






NOTES:

# - import or inlcude a library (preprocessor directive)
.h - header file
swtiches (-std=c99 -pedantic -Wall -Wextra) --> should be in the gcc command
    -std=c99 (standard)
    -pedantic (giving all information; check everything for the standard)
    -Wall & - Wextra(turn on all and extra warnings)
    rest are feedback to computer
executable - default is (a.out) & ./ is referring to somehting in current directory

3 steps of gcc:
    1. preprocessor - scans the code and find ones that start with #
    2. compiler - turn human-readable source code into object code
    3. linker - link all dot C files into one executable one

%(data type) - place holder
    d - decimal (integer type, ld for long int)
    u - unsigned (integer type that disallows negatives, lu for long unsigned)
    f - floating point (single-precision floating point number) --> (lf for double)
    c - character
    s - string
    booleans: no bool, if want to use can either 1. #include <stdbool.h> OR 2. use integers (0/1 as T/F)
          i.e.:
                #include <stdio.h> //standard input output library
                int main(){
                    int d = 36;
                    printf("There are %d students in class.", d);
                    return 0; } // return 0 serves as a signal of success

Operators
  ・add (+)
  ・subtract (-)
  ・multiplication (*)
  ・division (/) ; truncates decimal //i.e. 7/2 --> 3
  ・remainder (%)
  i.e.:
        #include <stdio.h>
        int main(void) {
            int fahrenheit = 75;
            float celsius = 5.0 / 9.0 * (fahrenheit - 32);
            printf("%0.2f", celsius); //2 decimals
        return 0;}
  ・const - put b4 the type to say a variable cannot be modified

Read from user:
  scanf - reading from user input (returns a value)
      if 0 - invalid input
      if -1 - no input at all
  i.e.:
    int i;
    printf("Please enter an integer: ");
    scanf("%d", &i); //can return how many vals r read
    printf("The value you entered is %d", i);





EXCERCISE:
//Write a program that reads two integer numbers as input and prints the sum of them
    #include <stdio.h>
    int main(){
        int i;
        int x;
        printf("Please enter an integer: ");
        scanf("%d", &i);
        printf("Please enter an integer: ");
        scanf("%d", &x);
        printf("The sum of the value you entered is %d", i+x);
     return 0; }
